## Tech stack

Foundational tier (React/TypeScript/Tailwind/shadcn/Lucide/Vitest/axe-core) is unchanged from the template default — see `30-react-stack.mdc`.

Deviations and additions from the template baseline (recorded here per the guardrails' own rule):

- **Build/routing — Next.js App Router (React 19 / Next 16), not Vite.** A documented Tier-1/Tier-3 deviation: the app needs a single full-stack codebase (UI + route handlers + server actions) for PostGIS spatial queries, server-side multi-tenant scoping, scheduled feed/AI jobs, and the premium engine. Ships `output: 'standalone'` + a Dockerfile for host portability (Cloud Run primary target, Vercel fallback). Next 16 (the latest available at implementation time, superseding the originally-planned Next 15) renamed the `middleware.ts` file convention to `proxy.ts` — see `src/proxy.ts`.
- **Test environment — Vitest + `happy-dom`, not `jsdom`.** A documented Tier-2 deviation from the template default: this build's `jsdom@29` dependency chain (`whatwg-url`/`html-encoding-sniffer` → `@exodus/bytes`) ships ESM-only files that Vitest's forked worker pool cannot `require()`, breaking `npm test` outright on this toolchain. `happy-dom` implements the same DOM surface React Testing Library and axe-core need without that broken chain.
- **Database — PostgreSQL + PostGIS (+ H3/pgrouting) via Prisma, hosted on Neon** (pooled connection string for runtime, direct/unpooled for migrations — the known Prisma+serverless connection-exhaustion pitfall). Geometry columns modelled as `Unsupported("geometry(...)")` with raw `$queryRaw`/`$executeRaw` for spatial predicates — Prisma has no native geometry type. Postgres Row-Level Security keyed on `clientId` (and `brokerOrganisationId`) sits underneath Prisma's own scoping as defense-in-depth.
- **Auth — Clerk** (template default, retained — not a deviation). Email OTP/magic-link only initially. Role (`INSURER_ADMIN`/`BROKER`/`CLIENT`) and scope (`clientId`/`brokerOrganisationId`) live as Clerk user metadata, carried into a session-token claim that Postgres RLS and Prisma scoping key on. No insured-person or financial data ever reaches Clerk.
- **Mapping — MapLibre GL JS (via react-map-gl) + deck.gl**, self-hosted PMTiles/Protomaps basemap, PostGIS-backed vector tiles via Martin for live risk layers. Chosen over Mapbox (paid beyond a free tier) and over Google Maps (whose terms forbid permanently storing/caching POI data, which the geofencing engine requires).
- **Data-dense tables — TanStack Table** (Tier 2 addition) for Endorsement history, cross-client rollups, and the ExternalSignal review queue: sortable, filterable, virtualized.
- **Charts — Recharts** (addition) for premium/aggregate trend charts, using the brand's fixed Indigo/Pink tint scales, not arbitrary opacities.
- **Background jobs — Inngest** (addition) for scheduled feed fetches and AI news-scan runs, keeping cron-style work durable and out of the request path.
- **AI provider — Anthropic API** (Tier-3 addition per `50-ai-tooling.mdc`) for both governed AI features (Structure Chat, news monitoring); retrieval-grounded/extractive only, evaluated against data-retention/DPA rejection criteria before any client personal data reaches a prompt.
- **Observability — Sentry** (addition) for error tracking/performance, wired per `62-deployment-observability.mdc`; structured JSON logs carry a correlation/request ID end-to-end.
- **E2E — Playwright** (template default, retained) added alongside Vitest for critical multi-role flows (login/role-switch, recalibration wizard, premium calculator, AI confirm).
- **API shape** — Next.js Route Handlers (`/api/v1/...`) for anything needing versioning/rate limiting/external integration; Server Actions for internal form mutations. Consistent error envelope: `{ error: { code, message, details?, requestId } }`. Mutating, retryable endpoints accept an idempotency key. Large lists use cursor-based pagination.

## Architecture decisions

- Multi-tenant, client-first / broker-second scoping: Insurer sees all clients; Broker sees only clients its BrokerOrganisation is assigned to (via `ClientBrokerAssignment`); Client sees only its own data. Enforced at both the Prisma query layer and Postgres RLS.
- Territory risk data is shared/global (one Insurer-maintained source of truth); everything else (`MemberOrganisation`, `OrganisationLocation`, `Policy` and its children, `RiskMixPolicy`, `RecalibrationBatch`) is scoped by `clientId`.
- AI features (Structure Chat, news monitoring) are strictly advisory and human-gated: the AI drafts against the real schema or extracts quoted, verified evidence; nothing is real or repriced until a human confirms. Every draft and decision is stored immutably for audit.
- Delete/update FK policy is explicit, not defaulted: financial/audit-bearing relationships (`Endorsement → OrganisationLocation`, `TerritoryRiskHistory → Territory`, `PolicyStructureSession → Policy`) are `RESTRICT`; purely compositional drafts may cascade.
- High-stakes actions (deleting a Territory, confirming an AI-drafted policy, reversing an Endorsement) always require an explicit, named confirm step.
- Agent governance: `.cursor/rules/` (advisory), `.cursor/hooks.json` (runtime), Husky + GitHub Actions (automation). Branch protection on `main` requires the CI jobs to pass before merge.

## Data classification (POPIA)

- Personal-information categories this app touches: insured person / employee names and details (via `OrganisationLocation` headcounts and any future member-level detail), Clerk login identity (email, name) for platform users. No insured-person or financial data is ever sent to Clerk or to the Anthropic API.
- Retention / anonymization: deletion requests against personal data are served by a tested anonymization code path that strips identifying fields while preserving the count/rate/history records the underwriting file depends on — hard-delete is not used, since it would destroy required underwriting evidence.
- Backup / retention window: Neon free-tier point-in-time-recovery window is 24 hours (Neon's free-plan default, not separately configurable) — sufficient for the current build/testing phase only. This must be revisited (Neon paid tier or Cloud SQL automated backups with a longer window, per client contractual/regulatory need) before the project holds anything beyond local/free-tier dev data.
- Real client data or secrets must never enter this repository (`.env`, exports, seed data with real names) — seed scripts use the workbook structure with anonymized/placeholder values only.
- Repo visibility: public (chosen deliberately — see below). Public visibility must never be treated as license to relax the no-real-data rule above; it is exactly why that rule is enforced instead.

## Out of scope / do not touch

- Claims management — no claims register, status tracking, or claims-ratio feed into risk scoring.
- Invoicing & payment reconciliation — the platform computes premium/aggregate figures only; no debtor/arrears tracking or bank-receipt reconciliation.
- Deeper SA insurance compliance beyond POPIA — no FAIS conduct-of-business features, binder-function workflow, or Policyholder Protection Rules tooling.
- Certificates of insurance / Policy Schedule PDF generation — not built; the brand's document spec is reference material only, kept in case this changes later.
- Do not commit `.env`, real client data, or credentials.
- Do not weaken CI, hooks, or security scans without explicit instruction.

## Repo visibility note

This repo is public. That decision was made deliberately, on a personal (non-Enterprise) GitHub account, to unlock two features that are otherwise unavailable: branch protection on `main` (Free plan blocks this on private repos; Pro would unlock it) and CI build-provenance attestation (unavailable on private repos below GitHub Enterprise Cloud — Pro/Team do not unlock it). Public visibility is safe here specifically because of the no-real-data rule above: this repo's source code is never supposed to contain real client/insured-person data or secrets. Before any real client data enters the *running application* (not the repo), ownership must move to a Lombard-owned GCP project/billing account as already noted in the platform plan — that is a separate, hosting-level concern from repo visibility.
